Defines the `ctx-scan` CLI surface (clap `Cli`/`Mode`) and the entry points the binary calls after parsing: `list_targets`, `check`, `stop_hook`, and `dispatch`. This is where run-mode selection and output rendering live; `runner.rs` does the actual work (`check_run`, `scan_run`, `update_run`), `hash.rs` defines `Staleness`, and `walker.rs` provides `walk_dir`.

Modes (`dry_run`, `check`, `update`, `stop_hook`) are mutually exclusive via clap's `conflicts_with`/`conflicts_with_all`; `dispatch` only handles the plain-scan vs. `--update` split; `dry_run`/`check`/`stop_hook` are dispatched elsewhere (presumably `main.rs`) directly to `list_targets`/`check`/`stop_hook`.

`stop_hook` is deliberately report-only: it recomputes staleness with `check_run` and emits a `{"systemMessage": ...}` JSON line, but never calls the agent — the doc comment explains this is because Claude Code's Stop event fires per-turn, not at session end, so regeneration here would race in-progress session state. It always treats a fresh tree as silent (`Ok(())` with no output), and the binary is expected to fail-open (swallow errors) at this call site — that fail-open behavior lives in the caller, not here.

`staleness_message` embeds the exact suggested follow-up command, including conditionally appending ` --approve` when `changed_files.len() > ctx_summarize::runner::MAX_TARGETS` — keep this threshold logic in sync with wherever `MAX_TARGETS` is enforced for real (`runner.rs`/`ctx_summarize::runner`), since the hint text can drift from the actual gate.

`validate_dir` canonicalizes and requires an existing directory (`ScanError::DirNotFound`), used by every entry point — no entry point runs against a non-existent or relative-only path silently. `render`/`render_staleness` are plain formatters producing the CLI's line-oriented human output (`stale-dir:`, `stale-leaf:`, `orphan-leaf:`, `missing-artifact:`, or `fresh`); this text format isn't a stable contract but any external tooling parsing stdout would care about it.